<observation>
Another option is to take advantage of the fact that the determinant is linear 
in each row or column.  This approach is called
<term>Laplace expansion</term> or <term>cofactor expansion</term>. 

For example, since 
\textcolor{blue}{<m>
  \left[\begin{array} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 4 \end{array}\right] 
= 
  1\left[\begin{array} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \end{array}\right]
+
  2\left[\begin{array} 0 &amp; 1 &amp;  0 \end{array}\right]
+
  4\left[\begin{array} 0  &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right]
</m>},

  \begin{align*}
\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 5  \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\ \textcolor{blue}{1} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{2} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{4} \end{array}\right] &amp;=
\textcolor{blue}{1}\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 5  \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\ \textcolor{blue}{1} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{0} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{0} \end{array}\right] +
\textcolor{blue}{2}\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 5  \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\ \textcolor{blue}{0} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{1} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{0} \end{array}\right] +
\textcolor{blue}{4}\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 5  \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\ \textcolor{blue}{0} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{0} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{1} \end{array}\right] \\
&amp;= -1\det \left[\begin{array}  5 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 \\ 5 &amp; 3 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right] 
-2\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 5 &amp; 3  \\ -1 &amp; 5 &amp; 3 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right] +
4\det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 5  \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 \\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \end{array}\right] \\
&amp;= -\det \left[\begin{array} 5 &amp; 3 \\ 5 &amp; 3 \end{array}\right] 
-2 \det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 5 \\ -1 &amp; 5 \end{array}\right]
+4 \det \left[\begin{array} 2 &amp; 3 \\ -1 &amp; 3 \end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

</observation>

<observation>
Applying Laplace expansion to a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix yields a short formula you may have seen:
<me>
  \det \left[\begin{array} \textcolor{blue}{a} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{b} \\ c &amp; d \end{array}\right]
=
  \textcolor{blue}{a}\det \left[\begin{array} \textcolor{blue}{1} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{0} \\ 
    c &amp; d \end{array}\right] 
+ 
  \textcolor{blue}{b} \det \left[\begin{array} \textcolor{blue}{0} &amp; \textcolor{blue}{1} \\ 
    c &amp; d \end{array}\right] 
=
  a\det \left[\begin{array} \textcolor{red}{1} &amp; \textcolor{red}{0} \\ 
    \textcolor{red}{c} &amp; d \end{array}\right] 
-
  b \det \left[\begin{array} \textcolor{red}{1} &amp; \textcolor{red}{0} \\ 
    \textcolor{red}{d} &amp; c \end{array}\right] 
= 
  ad-bc
.</me>

\vspace{1em}

There are formulas for the determinants of larger matrices,
but they can be pretty tedious to use. For example, writing out a
formula for a <m>4\times 4</m> determinant would require 24 different terms!

<me>
   \det\left[\begin{array}
     a_{11} &amp; a_{12} &amp; a_{13} &amp; a_{14} \\
     a_{21} &amp; a_{22} &amp; a_{23} &amp; a_{24} \\
     a_{31} &amp; a_{32} &amp; a_{33} &amp; a_{34} \\
     a_{41} &amp; a_{42} &amp; a_{43} &amp; a_{44}
   \end{array}\right]
     =
   a_{11}(a_{22}(a_{33}a_{44}-a_{43}a_{34})-a_{23}(a_{32}a_{44}-a_{42}a_{34})+\dots)+\dots
</me>

So this is why we either use Laplace expansion or row/column operations directly.
</observation>


